metadata.name: The Summoning #103
CrossWorlds #315
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180°
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Alienpillars #97
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: Borromean Nymph #5
metadata.description:
Language designates unconscious discourses in subjects, can we recreate the language that constitutes us? 

To go beyond the simulacrum of figuration and enter into the formless, to restore the signifiers of our ancestors and awaken the hidden power in the invisible, to understand no longer from words but by opening ourselves to uncertainty, to chance and to error. 

To blur the limits of the imaginary and symbolic to enter into the real is to understand the magic, to recreate the impossible.

metadata.name: Abstract Snails #24
metadata.description:
This piece is the first of a series of pieces created using an algorithm that's based on an invisible particle system. The particles themselves are not rendered but only the space between those that are in close proximity. 

Assigning different rules to these particles creates very interesting patterns. In this piece they are taught to move in ever increasing circles creating a snail pattern. 

Colors, stroke width, straight/curved lines are determined by the hash. In some iterations particles will gravitate to each other, creating a more chaotic pattern. 

Creating using vanilla JS on a 2D-Canvas.


Controls:
S - Save 2000x2000 image
Space - Pause/Unpause animation
Up/Down-Arrows - Increase/Decrease speed

metadata.name: Digital Monolith 160 #39
metadata.description:
This is my first monolith here on fxhash (and the first generative version of it too).

The artwork represents the exchange of digital data, like in networks or other electronic processes.

This is a collaboration with @andrew0 who wrote the code and created the music tracks (click to start audio if it doesn’t start automatically).

There are 4 sets of moving cubes, and a total of 16 different colors, plus 4 different core cubes and 7’different backgrounds. 

Audio loops follow the different backgrounds, while percussive sounds follow the cubes cores.

All sounds are tuned to A to 432hz and are created using the Arturia library and Logic Pro DAW.
